ed on the showroom platform, framed by the curtain and plant, then rolls away to the right.\n\nA circular sign appears against a brick wall with the words “1955 DeSoto.” The circle opens visually into a front view of the real car, transitioning from animation into live-action footage. The car faces forward, centered against a plain light background at first. Its broad chrome grille, rounded headlights, hood ornament, and front license plate are prominent. The plate reads “ZX 44843.” The car then appears driving toward the viewer on a wide open road, with a flat horizon and distant landscape behind it. The chrome grille and bumper catch the light, and the windshield shows occupants inside.\n\nThe DeSoto is shown from multiple angles while driving. From the side, it is a long, low two-door car with a hardtop roofline, large whitewall tires, and a sweeping contrasting side treatment along the body. From the rear three-quarter angle, its fins, rear lights, trunk shape, and wide rear bumper are visible as it moves away along the road. The setting is open and spacious, like a highway or test road, with little traffic and a broad sky.\n\nThe commercial returns to animation. A group of cartoon pedestrians stands along a city sidewalk in front of a wall. They are drawn in varied shapes and styles: a short person with round glasses and a brimmed hat, a tall narrow man with a long face, a woman in a fitted light dress and wide-brimmed hat, and others clustered behind them. Their bodies face the street and their heads turn as a DeSoto passes across the foreground from right to left. They appear to stop and look, smiling or staring with interest as the car goes by. After it passes, the group remains gathered, still oriented toward where the car went.\n\nA stylized residential street appears, with several houses lined up side by side. The houses have sharp triangular roofs, square windows, bare trees, and a flat sidewalk in front. A DeSoto drives into view along the street and stops or slows in front of the homes. As it appears, people begin showing up in the windows and doorways: figures lean out from upstairs and downstairs windows, a person stands on an upper balcony or porch, and others peer from neighboring houses. Their heads and upper bodies angle toward the car. The DeSoto sits below them at curb level, its side profile visible, again with the long body, whitewall tires, and sweeping two-tone side design. The car visually becomes the center of attention in the neighborhood scene.\n\nThe view changes to the real car’s interior. A large pale steering wheel fills the left side, with a shiny chrome-and-metal dashboard stretching across the frame. The instrument panel has several round gauges and dials arranged in a balanced, cockpit-like layout. The surfaces are glossy and reflective. A close view emphasizes a small control lever mounted on the dashboard near the gauges, projecting outward from a chrome base. This appears to be the feature identified in the commercial context as the “flight control lever.” The lever sits conveniently near the driver’s side controls, with surrounding knobs and circular instruments visible.\n\nThe image dissolves back to the animated neighborhood, where the DeSoto remains parked or displayed at the curb. Cartoon people stand around it: a man at the left, a person near the rear, and a woman at the right in a skirt or dress. The car’s side is emphasized, especially the dramatic contrasting sweep along the body that starts near the front and flows rearward. In black and white, the “color sweep” reads as a bold lighter-and-darker slash across the side panels.\n\nThe real DeSoto returns on the open road, now shown in a front three-quarter view. It moves smoothly across the pavement with the horizon behind it. Its chrome grille, hood ornament, rounded headlights, whitewall tires, and contrasting side sweep are all visible. Large cursive on-screen writing appears over the road scene, reading “Smartest of the Smart Cars.” The word “Smartest” stretches widely above the car, while “of the Smart Cars” appears below in flowing script. The text fades, leaving the car continuing along the highway.\n\nThe final views return to the car in motion from the side. The DeSoto travels steadily across a flat, open landscape, its long profile and low stance clearly shown. The hardtop roof, broad rear fender, whitewall wheels, and sweeping side trim remain visible as the commercial ends with the automobile moving confidently along the road.",
